To update widgets whenever your app opens, you'll need to add code to send broadcasts to your widget providers in the appropriate app entry points. Let's modify your AndroidManifest.xml to ensure widgets are updated when the app launches.

```xml:app/src/main/AndroidManifest.xml
<application
 android:allowBackup="true"
 android:dataExtractionRules="@xml/data_extraction_rules"
 android:fullBackupContent="@xml/backup_rules"
 android:icon="@mipmap/ic_launcher"
 android:label="@string/app_name"
 android:roundIcon="@mipmap/ic_launcher"
 android:supportsRtl="true"
 android:theme="@style/Theme.Ken"
 android:name=".KenApplication"
 tools:targetApi="31" >
 <!-- No changes needed in the manifest file -->
</application>
```

The AndroidManifest.xml doesn't need changes. Instead, you need to modify your app's entry points to trigger widget updates.

Here's what you should do:

1. Modify your KenApplication class to update widgets on app start:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/yourpackage/ken/KenApplication.kt
class KenApplication : Application() {
 override fun onCreate() {
 super.onCreate()
 // Other initialization code

 // Update all widgets when app starts
 updateAllWidgets()
