@Composable
fun MenuButton(onClick: () -> Unit, drawerProgress: Float = 0f) {
 // Calculate transition values based on drawer progress
 val yOffset = lerp(0f, -100f, drawerProgress) // Move up by 100dp when drawer fully open
 val alpha = lerp(1f, 0f, drawerProgress) // Fade out as drawer opens

 Icon(
 imageVector = Icons.Default.Menu,
 contentDescription = "Menu",
 tint = Color.White,
 modifier = Modifier
 .padding(top = 29.sdp, start = 23.dp)
 .offset(y = yOffset.dp) // Apply vertical offset
 .alpha(alpha) // Apply transparency
 .border(
 border = BorderStroke(2.sdp, Color.DarkGray),
 shape = RoundedCornerShape(5.sdp)
 )
 .size(32.sdp)
 .padding(4.sdp)
 .clickable(onClick = onClick, enabled = alpha > 0.1f) // Disable clicks when mostly faded out
 .background(colorResource(R.color.bg_neutral))
 )
}
```

## Explanation

I've made the following changes:

1. Added a `drawerProgress` parameter (ranging from 0.0 to 1.0) that tracks the drawer's open state
2. Pass this progress value through the component hierarchy:
 - From `DashboardContent` to `ScreenContents`
 - From `ScreenContents` to `DashboardHeader`
 - From `DashboardHeader` to `MenuButton`
3. In the `MenuButton`:
 - Added a vertical offset that moves the button upward as the drawer opens
 - Added alpha transparency that fades out the button as the drawer opens
 - Disabled click events when the button is mostly transparent

The `lerp` function creates a smooth transition between two values based on the progress. When the drawer is closed (progress = 0), the menu button is fully visible and in its normal position. As the drawer opens, the button smoothly transitions upward and fades away until it's completely invisible when the drawer is fully open.

This creates the clean transition effect you requested - the button doesn't just disappear but gracefully animates off-screen when the drawer opens and animates back when it closes."},{"role":"user","content":"<user_query>
