You're right that a fixed drawer width ratio might not work well across all screen sizes. Let's make the drawer width more adaptable based on screen size.

Here's how we can update the drawer width calculation:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/devrachit/ken/presentation/screens/dashboard/ActivityContent/DrawerLayoutContentComposable.kt
// ... existing code ...

@Composable
fun DrawerLayoutContent(username: String, uiState: States) {
 val coroutineScope = rememberCoroutineScope()
 val configuration = LocalConfiguration.current
 val screenWidthDp = configuration.screenWidthDp

 // Improved drawer width calculation based on screen size
 val drawerWidth = when {
 screenWidthDp >= 600 -> (screenWidthDp * 0.5f).dp.coerceAtMost(400.dp) // Larger screens: 50% width up to 400dp
 screenWidthDp >= 360 -> (screenWidthDp * 0.75f).dp.coerceAtMost(320.dp) // Medium screens: 75% width up to 320dp
 else -> screenWidthDp.dp.coerceAtMost(280.dp) // Small screens: Nearly full width up to 280dp
 }

 // ... existing code ...
}
```

This approach:
1. For larger screens (tablets, >600dp width): Uses 50% of screen width up to 400dp max
2. For medium-sized phones (>360dp width): Uses 75% of screen width up to 320dp max (your current logic)
3. For smaller phones: Uses a wider proportion of the screen up to 280dp max

You can adjust these thresholds and percentages to suit your specific design needs. This ensures the drawer is usable on small screens while not being excessively wide on larger tablets."},{"role":"user","content":"<additional_data>
