Yes, you should explicitly provide the UseCase in a module. While Hilt can automatically generate factories for classes with `@Inject` constructors, it's a best practice to explicitly provide your use cases in a dedicated module for better organization and clarity.

Let's create a `UseCaseModule`:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/devrachit/ken/di/modules/UseCaseModule.kt
package com.devrachit.ken.di.modules

import com.devrachit.ken.domain.policy.CachePolicy
import com.devrachit.ken.domain.repository.local.LeetcodeLocalRepository
import com.devrachit.ken.domain.repository.remote.LeetcodeRemoteRepository
