This error is related to the Room database schema directory configuration. It's happening because there's an issue with the schema directory path format in your Room configuration.

## The Problem

The error message indicates that the schema directory path format is incorrect. It should be in the format of `\S+=\S+`, but there seems to be an issue with the path:

```
room.internal.schemaInput=E:\Nodejs Projects\Ken\app\schemas
```

The backslashes in the Windows path are causing the issue, as they're being interpreted as escape characters.

## How to Fix It

There are two ways to fix this:

### Option 1: Fix the room {} block in build.gradle.kts

```kotlin:app/build.gradle.kts
// Change this:
room {
 schemaDirectory("$projectDir/schemas")
}

// To this:
room {
 schemaDirectory("${projectDir.path}/schemas")
}
```

The `projectDir.path` will ensure proper path formatting for your operating system.

### Option 2: Use forward slashes even on Windows

```kotlin:app/build.gradle.kts
room {
 schemaDirectory("$projectDir/schemas")
}
```

Gradle usually handles path conversions properly when using forward slashes, even on Windows.

## Alternative Solution

If the above solutions don't work, try creating an absolute path without using `projectDir`:

```kotlin:app/build.gradle.kts
room {
 schemaDirectory(File(rootDir, "app/schemas").absolutePath)
}
```

## Additional Steps

1. Make sure the schemas directory exists:
 ```
 mkdir -p app/schemas
 ```

2. Clean and rebuild your project:
 ```
 ./gradlew clean
 ./gradlew build
 ```

3. If you're using Windows paths with backslashes, make sure they're properly escaped in Kotlin strings:
 ```kotlin
 room {
 schemaDirectory("${projectDir.absolutePath.replace("\\", "/")}\\schemas")
 }
 ```

This should resolve the schema directory path issue in your Room configuration."},{"role":"user","content":"<user_query>
