You're right - the API is being called twice because `loadUserDetails()` is called in both `onCreate()` and `onResume()`. Let's fix this by calling it only once:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/devrachit/ken/presentation/screens/dashboard/ActivityContent/MainActivity.kt
// ... existing imports ...

@AndroidEntryPoint
class MainActivity : ComponentActivity() {

 val viewModel: MainViewModel by viewModels()
 private var isInitialLoad = true // Add this flag

 override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
 super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
 setupWindow()
 val username = intent.getStringExtra(NAVKEYUSERNAME) ?: "Guest_User"

 // Load user details only on initial creation
 viewModel.loadUserDetails()
 isInitialLoad = false

 setContent {
 val uiStates = viewModel.userValues.collectAsStateWithLifecycle().value
 DashboardContent(username=username,uiState= uiStates)
 }
 }

 override fun onResume() {
 super.onResume()
 // Only load data if it's not the initial load
 if (isInitialLoad.not()) {
 viewModel.loadUserDetails()
 }
 }

 // ... rest of your code ...
}
```

This approach:
1. Adds a flag `isInitialLoad` to track if this is the first time the activity is loading
2. Calls `loadUserDetails()` in `onCreate()` and sets the flag to `false`
3. In `onResume()`, only calls `loadUserDetails()` if it's not the initial load

This way, when the activity is first created, the API is called only once, and when the user returns to the activity from another screen, the data gets refreshed.

Alternatively, if you want a more robust approach that's lifecycle-aware, you could use a ViewModel with saved state:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/devrachit/ken/presentation/screens/dashboard/ActivityContent/MainViewModel.kt
